The paper proposes a method for designing and analyzing ultra-large scale (ULS) systems using measures of complexity, emergence, self-organization, and homeostasis based on information theory. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Systems and Control (cs.SY). Additionally, the use of information theory suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Information Theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the use of adaptation mechanisms, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI). The use of computing systems suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). Finally, the discussion of optimization and performance suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE).
